# 5. Difference between WHERE and HAVING

## WHERE

Filters individual rows before grouping.

Example

```sql
SELECT *
FROM Employees
WHERE Salary > 50000;
```

---

## HAVING

Filters grouped data after GROUP BY.

Example

```sql
SELECT Department,
COUNT(*)
FROM Employees
GROUP BY Department
HAVING COUNT(*) > 5;
```

### Comparison

| WHERE                                    | HAVING                       |
| ---------------------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Filters rows                             | Filters groups               |
| Used before GROUP BY                     | Used after GROUP BY          |
| Cannot directly filter aggregate results | Can filter aggregate results |

---

# 6. Difference between Primary Key and Foreign Key

## Primary Key

A Primary Key uniquely identifies every row in a table.

Characteristics

* Unique
* Cannot be NULL
* One primary key per table

Example

```sql
EmpID INT PRIMARY KEY
```

---

## Foreign Key

A Foreign Key creates a relationship between two tables.

Example

```sql
DepartmentID INT,
FOREIGN KEY (DepartmentID)
REFERENCES Department(DepartmentID);
```

### Comparison

| Primary Key        | Foreign Key                            |
| ------------------ | -------------------------------------- |
| Unique             | May contain duplicate values           |
| Cannot be NULL     | Can contain NULL (depending on design) |
| Identifies records | Creates relationships                  |

---

# 7. Difference between Primary Key and Unique Key

| Primary Key                | Unique Key                              |
| -------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Cannot contain NULL values | Usually allows one NULL (DBMS-specific) |
| Only one per table         | Multiple unique keys allowed            |
| Used for identification    | Used to enforce uniqueness              |

### Interview Tip

Every Primary Key is unique, but not every Unique Key is a Primary Key.

